Let $\omega = e^{\frac{2\pi}{n}i} = \cos \frac{2\pi}{n} + i \sin \frac{2\pi}{n}$, a primitive $n$th root of unity. Then \begin{align*}
  \cos \frac{\pi}{n} \cos \frac{2\pi}{n} \cos \frac{4\pi}{n} \cos \frac{8\pi}{n}
     \cos \frac{16\pi}{n} &= \operatorname{Re} \omega \operatorname{Re} \omega^2 \operatorname{Re} \omega^4 \operatorname{Re} \omega^8 \operatorname{Re} \omega^{16} \\
             &= \frac{\operatorname{Re} \omega + \operatorname{Re} \omega^2 + \operatorname{Re} \omega^4 + \operatorname{Re} \omega^8 + \operatorname{Re} \omega^{16}}{1} \\
             &= \frac{1 - \omega^{16}}{16\operatorname{Re}\left( \frac{\omega^{16} - 1}{\omega - 1} \right)} \\
    &= \frac{-1}{16\operatorname{Re}\left( \frac{\omega^{16} - 1}{\omega - 1} \right)}
\end{align*}Conversely, if the roots of unity $\omega_1, \omega_2, \dots, \omega_{n - 1}$ satisfy \[\frac{\omega_n - 1}{\omega_n + 1} = \frac{-1}{16\operatorname{Re}\left( \frac{\omega^{16} - 1}{\omega - 1} \right)},\] then \[\omega_1 + \omega_2 + \dots + \omega_{n - 1} = 0,\]which is obvious from geometric series. Thus, if the $n$th roots of unity $\omega_1, \omega_2, \dots, \omega_{n - 1}$ satisfy \[\frac{\omega_n - 1}{\omega_n + 1} = \frac{-1}{16\operatorname{Re}\left( \frac{\omega^{16} - 1}{\omega - 1} \right)},\] the product of the $\cos$ terms equals $\frac{1}{32}$. We have \begin{align*}
    \frac{\omega^k - 1}{\omega^k + 1}
     &= \frac{2i\sin \frac{k\pi}{n}}{2\cos \frac{k\pi}{n}} \\
     &= i\tan \frac{k\pi}{n} \\
     &= i\tan \frac{(i\dfrac{n}{k}\pi)}{(i\dfrac{n}{k})} \\
\end{align*}Thus, the roots of unity that satisfy the given product are the $n$th roots of unity for which $|\dfrac{n}{k}| = 16$, or equivalently, $k \divides 16n$. If $|\dfrac{n}{k}| = 16$, then $|\dfrac{\sin \dfrac{k\pi}{n}}{\cos \dfrac{k\pi}{n}}| = |\sin \frac{\pi}{16}|$. We know that $\sin z$ is monotonic on the interval $[0, \frac{\pi}{2}]$, so the only possible values of $\dfrac{n}{k}$ are 1, 2, 3, ..., 16. Thus, the $n$th roots of unity for which $|\dfrac{n}{k}| = 16$ are the $16n$th roots of unity. By Vieta's formulas, $1 + 2 + 4 + 8 + 16 = 31$. The $2n$th roots of unity are present twice, the $4n$th are present four times, the $8n$th are present eight times, and the $16n$th are present sixteen times. Furthermore, if a root of unity is present an even number of times, then its value cancels out. The only way for the sum to be $31$ is if $n$ is a multiple of $16$. The smallest positive multiple of $16$, $n = 16$, does not work. $n = 32$ does work, however. Therefore, the solutions are $\boxed{32}$.

